processinfo.head: Processing Information note
processinfo.p: Processing Level 2: Minimal processing has been conducted by Harold Oakhill, March 1994, to establish initial intellectual and physical control, address any immediate preservation concerns, and facilitate access to the holdings. Further processing of the records will be considered in the future, as necessary.
Materials remain in original record cartons and folders.
This guide provides file level description. Each file may represent multiple folders.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use note
userestrict.p: The Rockefeller Archive Center has title, copyright, and literary rights in the collection, in so far as it holds them, and has authority to grant permission to cite and publish archival material from the collection.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access note
accessrestrict.p: Open for research with select materials restricted as noted. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. Researchers interested in accessing digital media (floppy disks, CDs, DVDs, etc.) or audiovisual material (audio cassettes, VHS, etc.) in this collection must use an access surrogate. The original items may not be accessed because of preservation concerns. To request an access surrogate be made, or if you are unsure if there is an access surrogate, please contact an archivist.

Subseries 6: Trip files, Boxes 23, 192-197.

Subseries 9: Oversized items sent to the Vice President, Boxes 18, 25-38, 55, 56, 69.

Subseries 11: Control Slips and Control Cards, Boxes 212-215, 218-223.
Subseries 12: Correspondence Form Manual, Box 224.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: The Central Files series contains the general correspondence of the Office of the Vice President from Nelson A. Rockefeller's tenure (December 19, 1974, to January 20, 1977). The series offers partial documentation of Rockefeller's role in the development of national policy and his duties as President of the U.S. Senate. There is correspondence with President Gerald R. Ford and members of his staff, congressional representatives, senators, other government officials, and foreign dignitaries. However, there is very little in this series documenting actual policy formation. Much of the correspondence with government officials concerns the Vice President's information-gathering activities on behalf of the White House and executive agencies, as well as his support of the President's policies. There are also reports and position papers on national issues submitted to the Vice President by individuals both within and outside the federal government. Virtually all of these were unsolicited.
Also documented here are Rockefeller's campaign activities on behalf of President Ford and Senator Robert Dole in the 1976 presidential campaign.

The bulk of the correspondence consists of letters from U.S. citizens expressing their opinions on issues, inviting the Vice President to speak at events, asking for autographed photographs of the Vice President, or asking for the his assistance in securing an appointment to a federal agency or a military academy. The responses to such correspondence were written by the Vice President's staff.

Carbon copies of outgoing correspondence are filed in the name, subject, and chronological files. Routine incoming correspondence is filed in the name file, while incoming correspondence of significance was photocopied and filed in both the name and subject files. The chronological file contains only outgoing letters.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Invitations is arranged in 4 subseries: 1. General. 2. Domestic. 3. Foreign. 4. Other.
Domestic invitations are primarily filed by the year of the event/state or geographic area in which the event is being held in/city the event is being held in.
Each state or geographic area is assigned a number. The states are then arranged numerically/alphabetically. For example, ST 1 is Alabama, ST 2 is Alaska, ST 3 is Arizona and so on.

If a folder becomes too large to hold invitations from a particular state or geographic area, it is then divided alphabetically by the name of the city. Cities represented by a significant amount of documentation will have their own folder, or multiple folders.
Foreign invitations are primarily filed by the year of the event/country/city.
